From cou.: 1 Quantum spin-dependent transport in a ferromagnetic(FM)/DNA/ferromagnetic(FM) device is theoretically investigated based on the lattice Green function method and the Landauer–Büttiker theory. The effect of a transverse electric field on magnetoresistance (MR) of the device is investigated. It is predicted that either the direction or strength of the transverse electric field can change the MR of the device. We suggest a possible application of modulating MR of the FM/DNA/FM device by a transverse electric field.
From Soup: 1 Quantum spin-dependent transport in a ferromagnetic(FM)/DNA/ferromagnetic(FM) device is theoretically investigated based on the lattice Green function method and the Landauer–Büttiker theory. The effect of a transverse electric field on magnetoresistance (MR) of the device is investigated. It is predicted that either the direction or strength of the transverse electric field can change the MR of the device. We suggest a possible application of modulating MR of the FM/DNA/FM device by a transverse electric field.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Magnetic tunnel junction (MTJ) is extremely important for magnetic device application. Conventional MTJ sandwiches a thin nonmagnetic material between two ferromagnetic metals.1 The electric resistance of MTJ is sensitive to the relative magnetization of the ferromagnetic electrodes which results magnetoresistance. It is possible to change the resistance by controlling the magnetizations direction of the ferromagnetic electrodes through an external magnetic field.2 Organic materials have the advantage of weak spin–orbit and hyperfine interactions, which preserve spin-coherence over times and distances much longer than that in conventional metals or semiconductors. Such features make them suitable materials for spin injection and transport. Tsukagoshi et al.3 reported the injection of spin-polarized electrons from ferromagnetic electrodes into multi-walled carbon nanotubes. They observed a magnetoresistance in several nanotubes with a maximum resistance change of 9%. Xiong et al.4 designed the LSMO/Alq3/Co device and reported a magnetoresistance as high as 40%. Dediu et al.5 reported sexithienyl (T6) contacted by LSMO electrodes showing a strong magnetoresistance up to 30%. Petta et al.6 fabricated MTJ of octanethiol contacted by Ni and found a magnetoresistance up to 16%. Theoretically, for instance, Mehrez et al.7 used a tight binding model and investigated spin-coherent quantum transport in a single-wall carbon nanotube MTJ. Their calculation showed a magnetoresistance as large as 20% at low temperature. Waldron et al.8 studied quantum spin transport through a Ni-benzenedithiol (BDT)-Ni molecular MTJ. They took into account microscopic details based on the density functional theory and obtained magnetoresistance as large as 27%.
From Soup: 2 Magnetic tunnel junction (MTJ) is extremely important for magnetic device application. Conventional MTJ sandwiches a thin nonmagnetic material between two ferromagnetic metals. 1 The electric resistance of MTJ is sensitive to the relative magnetization of the ferromagnetic electrodes which results magnetoresistance. It is possible to change the resistance by controlling the magnetizations direction of the ferromagnetic electrodes through an external magnetic field. 2 Organic materials have the advantage of weak spin–orbit and hyperfine interactions, which preserve spin-coherence over times and distances much longer than that in conventional metals or semiconductors. Such features make them suitable materials for spin injection and transport. Tsukagoshi et al. 3 reported the injection of spin-polarized electrons from ferromagnetic electrodes into multi-walled carbon nanotubes . They observed a magnetoresistance in several nanotubes with a maximum resistance change of 9%. Xiong et al. 4 designed the LSMO/Alq 3 /Co device and reported a magnetoresistance as high as 40%. Dediu et al. 5 reported sexithienyl ( T 6 ) contacted by LSMO electrodes showing a strong magnetoresistance up to 30%. Petta et al. 6 fabricated MTJ of octanethiol contacted by Ni and found a magnetoresistance up to 16%. Theoretically, for instance, Mehrez et al. 7 used a tight binding model and investigated spin-coherent quantum transport in a single-wall carbon nanotube MTJ. Their calculation showed a magnetoresistance as large as 20% at low temperature. Waldron et al. 8 studied quantum spin transport through a Ni-benzenedithiol (BDT)-Ni molecular MTJ. They took into account microscopic details based on the density functional theory and obtained magnetoresistance as large as 27%.
