From cou.: 3 DNA is a promising candidate for molecular electronics because of its unique self-assembling and self-recognition properties which are essential for its performance as carrier of the genetic code. Its double stranded helix structure was discovered by Watson and Crick in 1953. As early as 1962, Eley and Spivey9 suggested that the interbase hybridization of πz orbitals perpendicular to the planes of the stacked base pairs in double-stranded DNA could lead to conducting behavior. Recently, many direct charge transport experiments have obtained the current–voltage characteristics of the device by contacting DNA molecules between two electrodes.10–17 Theoretically, Berlin et al.18–22 studied the charge transport mechanism in DNA. Grozema et al.23–25 used a tight binding approach to study the length and sequence dependence of the charge migration rate in DNA. The first principle density functional theory is also used to study DNA electronics.26–29 Although there exists some controversy about the conductivity of DNA, it is believed that DNA with artificially created periodic sequence, for example, such as the poly(A)-poly(T) or poly(G)-poly(C) DNA, can be a good candidate for a nanostructure device in suitable temperature, substrate and humidity environment.30
From Soup: 3 DNA is a promising candidate for molecular electronics because of its unique self-assembling and self-recognition properties which are essential for its performance as carrier of the genetic code. Its double stranded helix structure was discovered by Watson and Crick in 1953. As early as 1962, Eley and Spivey 9 suggested that the interbase hybridization of π z orbitals perpendicular to the planes of the stacked base pairs in double-stranded DNA could lead to conducting behavior. Recently, many direct charge transport experiments have obtained the current–voltage characteristics of the device by contacting DNA molecules between two electrodes. 10–17 Theoretically, Berlin et al. 18–22 studied the charge transport mechanism in DNA. Grozema et al. 23–25 used a tight binding approach to study the length and sequence dependence of the charge migration rate in DNA. The first principle density functional theory is also used to study DNA electronics. 26–29 Although there exists some controversy about the conductivity of DNA, it is believed that DNA with artificially created periodic sequence, for example, such as the poly(A)-poly(T) or poly(G)-poly(C) DNA, can be a good candidate for a nanostructure device in suitable temperature, substrate and humidity environment. 30
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 DNA is also used to explore the quantum spin transport. Zwolak and Ventra31 first showed that a DNA spin valve can be realized. They studied the DNA molecule contacted with Ni and Fe electrodes. They showed that magnetoresistance values of as much as 26% for Ni and 16% for Fe electrodes can be observed. They suggested the larger magnetoresistance for the Ni electrodes than for Fe ones is due to the larger mismatch between spin-up and spin-down Fermi velocities of Ni with respect to Fe. Wang and Chakraborty further studied the spin flip effect on spin transport in a DNA molecule.32 They found an enhancement of magnetoresistance for a weak spin flip coupling while an oscillatory behavior for a strong spin flip coupling. Recently, another interesting phenomenon was reported based on a poly(G)-poly(C) DNA device. When a perpendicular electric field is applied on a DNA molecule, Malyshev33 predicted that the charge current through the molecule will be suppressed. The reason is that transverse electric field induces change of the electronic structure of a DNA molecule, which results in an adjustable conducting tunneling along the double stranded helix.
From Soup: 4 DNA is also used to explore the quantum spin transport. Zwolak and Ventra 31 first showed that a DNA spin valve can be realized. They studied the DNA molecule contacted with Ni and Fe electrodes. They showed that magnetoresistance values of as much as 26% for Ni and 16% for Fe electrodes can be observed. They suggested the larger magnetoresistance for the Ni electrodes than for Fe ones is due to the larger mismatch between spin-up and spin-down Fermi velocities of Ni with respect to Fe. Wang and Chakraborty further studied the spin flip effect on spin transport in a DNA molecule. 32 They found an enhancement of magnetoresistance for a weak spin flip coupling while an oscillatory behavior for a strong spin flip coupling. Recently, another interesting phenomenon was reported based on a poly(G)-poly(C) DNA device. When a perpendicular electric field is applied on a DNA molecule, Malyshev 33 predicted that the charge current through the molecule will be suppressed. The reason is that transverse electric field induces change of the electronic structure of a DNA molecule, which results in an adjustable conducting tunneling along the double stranded helix.
