From cou.: 89 I
From Soup: 89 When a transverse electric field is applied, the potential along the DNA chain will be adjusted due to the spacial structure of a DNA double helix. This modulation changes the electronic structure of the DNA molecule and further influences its transport property. Ref. 33 has predicted that a transverse electric field will suppress the current through the device. The reason is that the transverse electric field potential tends to make the on-site energy of the poly(G)-poly(C) DNA molecule into a “disorder”. This “disorder” changes the wave-function of the electron and further influences conductivity. Our calculation reveals that the suppression on the current is also related to the direction of the transverse electric field, which is denoted by phase φ 0 , as shown in Fig. 3 . Since the modulation is harmonic due to the double helix structure of DNA molecule, we choose the phase φ 0 = 0 to correspond to the direction that the transverse electric field points to from base G to base C of the first base pair. The modulated potential along a one-helix-period ploy(G)-poly(C) DNA G and C chain is shown in Fig. 2 for phase φ 0 = 0 and φ 0 = π. At a fixed strength of the transverse electric field the amplitude of the “disorder” is unchanged, but different directions change the shape of the modulation in detail, which will make a difference of the conductance. For a simple metal/DNA/metal device, Fig. 3 shows the dependence of the current on φ 0 for different strengths of the transverse electric field. The straight solid line corresponds to the case when the transverse electric field is absent. When the transverse electric field is turned on, the current has fluctuating behavior with φ 0 . With a larger transverse electric field fluctuation becomes more notable.
 ###### 
From cou.: 90 The parameters are set as follows in this paper. For a poly(G)-poly(C) DNA molecule, the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) is taken as on-site energies:33εG = 1.14 eV and εC = −1.06 eV. The hopping integral is set as34tG(C) = 0.3 eV and t⊥ = 0.1 eV, which are within reasonable parameter intervals.35 We choose a typical tight-binding parameter for the ferromagnetic electrodes:39τ = 1.5 eV and J = 1.5 eV. The Fermi level of the electrodes is supposed to be at the middle of the DNA band gap. Interfacial couplings are supposed to be spin independent and set to be 0.02 eV, which is consistent with other theoretical works to fit the experimental I–V curves.11 A low temperature of T = 30 K is applied in this work.
From Soup: 90 Then for a FM/DNA/FM device, we apply a transverse electric field and calculate MR of the device. The upper panel in Fig. 4 shows that the MR at V T = 0.4 V. The dashed line is a result of V T = 0 V, which gives a MR of 25.3% in the present parameters. The lower panel in Fig. 4 shows the corresponding dependence of the current on φ 0 corresponding to the P (solid line) and AP (dashed line) alignment of magnetization of the electrodes. It is found that the direction of the transverse electric field has a remarkable modulation to MR of the FM/DNA/FM device. MR can reach larger values at some special directions of the transverse electric field. To facilitate handling of the figures, we chose the reference point φ 0 = 0 as the symmetrical point of the DNA molecule, which corresponds to the direction that the transverse electric field points to from base G to base C of the first base pair. Departing from the symmetrical point, both the P and AP currents will be decreasing. At φ 0 = 0, we obtain the current I P = 9.93 nA, I AP = 8.57 nA, which gives . For a small departure, for example, φ 0 = 0.1π = 0.314, we obtain I P = 7.93 nA, I AP = 6.62 nA, which gives MR = 16.5%. The exact reason for the increasing of MR is complex as both I P and I AP will change with the direction of the field. A qualitative understanding may be that, with the change of the field direction, the conducting tunnels tend to move out of the conducting window in both P and AP configurations. We hope that more tunnels move into the conducting window in the P configuration and fewer tunnels do so in the AP one to get a higher MR. This case seems to appear with a suitable adjustment of the electric field direction. As shown in Fig. 3 , at φ 0 = π we obtain a MR of the device as high as 42.5%.
 ###### 
From cou.: 91 We firstly investigate a one-helix-period poly(G)-poly(C) DNA which consists of 11-base pairs. Fig. 1 shows the current–voltage characteristics of the device for parallel (P) and antiparallel (AP) alignment of the magnetization of electrodes. The magnetoresistance is defined as MR = (IP−IAP)/IP. The inset in Fig. 1 is the corresponding dependence of magnetoresistance on applied bias. MR of the device increases from 3.1% at 1.2 V to 25.3% at 4 V. The result is consistent with that of ref. 31. It should be mentioned that in ref. 31 the magnetization of the electrodes is characterized by the different hopping integral for majority and minority electrons, while here we describe the magnetization of the electrodes with different on-site energies.39,40 There should be no qualitative difference for the final conclusion.
From Soup: 91 As the enhancement of MR is the largest at φ 0 = π in the present case, we calculate the dependence of MR on the strength of the transverse electric field by fixing φ 0 = π, The result is shown in Fig. 5(a) . The corresponding current with parallel (solid line) and antiparallel (dashed line) alignment of magnetization of electrodes is shown in Fig. 5(b) . Both P and AP currents decrease with the increase of the transverse electric field and approach zero when the strength of the field is larger than 2 V, which means that the current may be blocked by a strong transverse electric field. However, if we check the MR, it is found that it first increases with the transverse electric field. At about V T = 1.1 V the MR reaches a maximum value as high as 83%. A MR of 83% is indeed abnormal. We note that at this point the current I P = 4.04 nA, while I AP = 0.69 nA. The current in the AP configuration is much less than that in the P configuration, therefore a large MR is expected. By the way, some experimental works also reported a high MR in the MTJ structure. For example, in one of the recent experiments, 41 the MR of Co/MgO/Co MTJ structure reaches as high as 507% (which equals 83.5% in our definition). Some theoretical work 42 also predicted a high MR (over 90% in our definition) in a MTJ structure.
