From cou.: 93 Then for a FM/DNA/FM device, we apply a transverse electric field and calculate MR of the device. The upper panel in Fig. 4 shows that the MR at VT = 0.4 V. The dashed line is a result of VT = 0 V, which gives a MR of 25.3% in the present parameters. The lower panel in Fig. 4 shows the corresponding dependence of the current on φ0 corresponding to the P (solid line) and AP (dashed line) alignment of magnetization of the electrodes. It is found that the direction of the transverse electric field has a remarkable modulation to MR of the FM/DNA/FM device. MR can reach larger values at some special directions of the transverse electric field. To facilitate handling of the figures, we chose the reference point φ0 = 0 as the symmetrical point of the DNA molecule, which corresponds to the direction that the transverse electric field points to from base G to base C of the first base pair. Departing from the symmetrical point, both the P and AP currents will be decreasing. At φ0 = 0, we obtain the current IP = 9.93 nA, IAP = 8.57 nA, which gives . For a small departure, for example, φ0 = 0.1π = 0.314, we obtain IP = 7.93 nA, IAP = 6.62 nA, which gives MR = 16.5%. The exact reason for the increasing of MR is complex as both IP and IAP will change with the direction of the field. A qualitative understanding may be that, with the change of the field direction, the conducting tunnels tend to move out of the conducting window in both P and AP configurations. We hope that more tunnels move into the conducting window in the P configuration and fewer tunnels do so in the AP one to get a higher MR. This case seems to appear with a suitable adjustment of the electric field direction. As shown in Fig. 3, at φ0 = π we obtain a MR of the device as high as 42.5%.
From Soup: 93 We have performed a theoretical study of the quantum spin transport in a FM/DNA/FM device based on the lattice Green function method and the Landauer-Büttiker theory. We explore a possible usage of a transverse electric field for enhancing the magnetoresistance of the FM/DNA/FM device. It is found the direction and strength of the transverse electric field will induce a modulation in the MR. The MR of the device can be enhanced at some special direction and strength of the transverse electric field. This enhancement of MR is related to the electronic structure change induced by the transverse electric field, which is a peculiar characteristics of a DNA device.
 ###### 
From cou.: 94 As the enhancement of MR is the largest at φ0 = π in the present case, we calculate the dependence of MR on the strength of the transverse electric field by fixing φ0 = π, The result is shown in Fig. 5(a). The corresponding current with parallel (solid line) and antiparallel (dashed line) alignment of magnetization of electrodes is shown in Fig. 5(b). Both P and AP currents decrease with the increase of the transverse electric field and approach zero when the strength of the field is larger than 2 V, which means that the current may be blocked by a strong transverse electric field. However, if we check the MR, it is found that it first increases with the transverse electric field. At about VT = 1.1 V the MR reaches a maximum value as high as 83%. A MR of 83% is indeed abnormal. We note that at this point the current IP = 4.04 nA, while IAP = 0.69 nA. The current in the AP configuration is much less than that in the P configuration, therefore a large MR is expected. By the way, some experimental works also reported a high MR in the MTJ structure. For example, in one of the recent experiments,41 the MR of Co/MgO/Co MTJ structure reaches as high as 507% (which equals 83.5% in our definition). Some theoretical work42 also predicted a high MR (over 90% in our definition) in a MTJ structure.
